# UI/UX — Nielsen heuristics

Every UI/UX change MUST be reviewed against Nielsen's 10 usability heuristics before merge.

## UI Elements Gallery (mandatory)

**Before creating or changing any UI element**, read [docs/ui-elements-gallery.md](../../docs/ui-elements-gallery.md):

1. Find an existing element to reuse (class, Material component, behavior).
2. Match documented **properties**, **style** (tokens/classes), and **behavior**.
3. If no element fits, add the new element to the gallery in the same PR.
4. Do not introduce ad-hoc buttons, colors, or form patterns outside the gallery.

## Checklist (per screen or flow)

| # | Heuristic | Issues application |
|---|-----------|-------------------|
| 1 | **Visibility of system status** | Loading/disabled during submit; notification badge; kanban drop feedback; toasts |
| 2 | **Match system / real world** | Domain terms from [domain-specification.md](../../docs/domain-specification.md); PT-BR labels; familiar tracker patterns (Kanban, ticket ID) |
| 3 | **User control & freedom** | Cancel/close on dialogs; back navigation; logout; avoid `disableClose` unless required |
| 4 | **Consistency & standards** | Gallery elements + `styles.scss`; same button hierarchy; no one-off hex colours |
| 5 | **Error prevention** | `mat-form-field` validation; confirm destructive actions |
| 6 | **Recognition over recall** | Visible nav, status filter, project cards — minimise memory load |
| 7 | **Flexibility & efficiency** | Header search; Enter on search; role-based menu shortcuts |
| 8 | **Aesthetic & minimalist** | Flat UI principles below; content over decoration; clear hierarchy |
| 9 | **Error recovery** | `.error` messages; toasts; empty states with next-step guidance |
| 10 | **Help & documentation** | Footer OpenAPI link; empty states; tooltips where labels are ambiguous |

## Flat UI design language

Issues follows **flat UI design** — the style popularized by Microsoft's Metro design language (Windows Phone, 2010) and continued in [Microsoft Fluent Design](https://www.microsoft.design/). Flat design favours clarity and function over ornamental depth; it is the baseline for enterprise and productivity apps.

Reference: [microsoft.design](https://www.microsoft.design/)

### Principles → Issues implementation

| Flat UI principle | Issues application |
|-------------------|-------------------|
| **Simple, minimal interfaces** | `.page` scaffold, ample whitespace (`$space-*`), no decorative chrome; one primary action per screen region |
| **Clean sans-serif typography** | Roboto; hierarchy via size, weight, and color (`.page-title`, `.page-subtitle`, `$text-*`) — not via ornament |
| **Bold, vibrant colors** | Navy chrome (`$base-background-color`), primary blue (`$base-active-color`), semantic reds/greens for errors/success |
| **Flat iconography** | Material Icons — geometric, line-based; icon-only header actions (menu, notifications) |
| **Simple buttons** | Solid fills (`.btn`), light shadow only where needed; square corners (`$radius-none`); no gradients or bevels |
| **Minimal illustrations** | `.empty-state` with text guidance; avoid stock art or heavy graphics in prod UI |
| **Mobile-ready layouts** | Responsive header wrap, `@media max-width: 750px` rules in `styles.scss` |

### What “flat” means here

Flat UI is **not** only square corners. It is a full visual system:

- **No skeuomorphism** — no faux textures, inset shadows, or 3D button effects
- **No heavy elevation** — use `$shadow-card` sparingly; no card “lift” on hover
- **Typography carries hierarchy** — headings, subtitles, and muted metadata replace visual clutter
- **Color blocks define regions** — navy header/footer, white panels, muted page background
- **Square geometry** — `$radius-none` on buttons, fields, cards, and chrome (Metro-influenced)

Tokens and classes: `src/main/webui/src/colors.scss`, `src/main/webui/src/styles.scss`. Element mapping: [ui-elements-gallery.md](../../docs/ui-elements-gallery.md).

| Role | Token / pattern |
|------|-----------------|
| Chrome (header, footer) | `$base-background-color` |
| Primary action | `$base-active-color` + `.btn` |
| Secondary action | `.btn-secondary` |
| Destructive | `.btn-cancel` / `$base-error-color` |
| Page background | `$surface-page` |
| Cards / panels | `$surface-card` + `$shadow-card` |
| Shape | `$radius-none` (square corners) |

**Do:** flat surfaces, solid button fills, Roboto, restrained shadows, accessible focus rings, whitespace.  
**Don't:** gradients, glossy effects, heavy drop shadows, playful hover lift, pill/circular chrome (unless gallery explicitly adds an exception), ad-hoc hex outside `colors.scss`.

## Before finishing a UI change

1. Confirm gallery compliance (reuse or extend [ui-elements-gallery.md](../../docs/ui-elements-gallery.md)).
2. Walk the Nielsen checklist for the affected flow.
3. Confirm flat UI principles (table above) — especially typography hierarchy and minimal ornament.
4. Extend `colors.scss` / `styles.scss` — avoid scattered hex in component SCSS.
5. Verify mobile (`@media max-width: 750px` in `styles.scss`).
6. Run affected `*.spec.ts` when behaviour changes.
7. Update [feature-catalog.md](../../docs/feature-catalog.md) when routes or labels change.

